    <h1>Scaffolded Guided Notes for <em>Equitable Learning</em></h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A catalog-wide instructional resource system designed to level the playing field for diverse learners. Built by hand, refined with AI, and proven in live classrooms.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <div class="problem-solution">
      <div class="problem-solution-col">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">The Problem</div>
        <p>Students in fully digital courses arrived with uneven study strategies and no physical touchpoint. Without structured scaffolding, students who already knew how to learn had a built-in advantage.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-solution-col">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">The Solution</div>
        <p>A catalog-wide system of printable Google Doc guided notes, built by hand and later scaled with custom GPTs, giving every learner a common baseline and reducing the gap between prepared and underprepared students.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Analyze</div>
      <h2>The problem: <em>equity starts at the starting line</em></h2>
      <p>Lumen Learning&rsquo;s mission is to support unprecedented learning for all students. After years of working closely with faculty, students, and course data, I kept noticing the same tension: our courseware was strong, but students arrived with very different levels of preparation. High-quality content alone doesn&rsquo;t close that gap, and students who already know how to learn have a structural advantage, and in a fully digital environment, that gap widens further.</p>
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>The debate:</strong> Some colleagues argued that note-taking is a skill students should develop independently. I agreed, but I also believed that <strong>withholding scaffolding in the name of skill-building is not equity.</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-row">
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Learner Gap</h3><p>Students entered with uneven study strategies. Digital-only content offered no physical touchpoint or organizational scaffold.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Equity Gap</h3><p>Students from under-resourced backgrounds were most disadvantaged by the absence of structured support materials.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Alignment Gap</h3><p>Instructor-written exams sometimes diverged from courseware emphasis, leaving students without a clear map of priorities.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Physical Gap</h3><p>Student feedback revealed a persistent desire for something tangible — material they could print, hold, and write in.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Design &amp; Develop</div>
      <h2>The solution: <em>simple, flexible, and printable</em></h2>
      <p>The format decision was deliberate: Google Docs, not a proprietary platform. Google Docs are universally accessible, easily copied and modified by students, and printable with no special login required.</p>
      <p>Each document followed the module outline exactly, organized by section headers matching the course&rsquo;s &ldquo;Learn It&rdquo; pages. The format blended fill-in-the-blank vocabulary, hierarchical structural outlines, and occasional open-ended reflection prompts, giving students a map of how concepts related without removing the work of engaging with the material.</p>

      <blockquote>&ldquo;With everything being online and so intangible, students said they were still craving something they could touch and write in.&rdquo;</blockquote>

      <p>The first set of guided notes was created entirely by hand. I worked through every module myself, reading the content, building each outline from scratch, and making deliberate decisions about what belonged and what didn&rsquo;t. It was time-intensive, but that firsthand engagement with the material shaped the quality of what I built.</p>
      <p>When ChatGPT became available, I developed custom GPTs trained on the course content and my formatting specifications to generate new module drafts at scale. This dramatically reduced development time while preserving the instructional approach I&rsquo;d established manually. I later documented the workflow and trained my team to use it, extending the system across the full course catalog.</p>

      <div class="callout slate">
        <p><strong>One key revision:</strong> Early iterations were too granular. Students would sometimes hunt for a single missing word rather than engaging with the concept. After observing this in my own classroom at Davidson College, I shifted toward more holistic outlines that invited synthesis over transcription.</p>
      </div>

      <img src="{{ '/images/projects/guided-notes-example.png' | url }}" alt="Example of guided notes for Psychological Foundations module" class="post-featured-image" />
    </div>

    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Implement &amp; Evaluate</div>
      <h2>From pilot to <em>catalog standard</em></h2>
      <p>Guided notes launched in Intro Psychology and spread quickly. Students printed them and brought them to class, faculty reported stronger student orientation in discussions, and Lumen&rsquo;s sales team recognized them as a differentiator with institutional partners. Based on that reception, guided notes became standard protocol across the catalog.</p>

      <div class="insight-row">
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>What worked</h3><p>Students who used printed notes arrived with a framework and could focus on deepening understanding rather than capturing basics. The physical artifact increased engagement and a sense of ownership.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>What I changed</h3><p>Overly specific prompts led students to disengage while searching for exact answers. Shifting to holistic outlines improved engagement and reduced the &ldquo;word search&rdquo; behavior noticeably.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="reflection">
        <h3>Design Reflection</h3>
        <p>This project reinforced something I believe deeply: the best instructional solutions are often the simplest ones. A Google Doc outperformed any proprietary tool, because it was accessible, flexible, printable, and student-controlled.</p>
        <p>It also validated the equity argument. Scaffolding is not the opposite of rigor. Done well, it&rsquo;s what makes rigor accessible to everyone, not just students who already know how to learn.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

